"""
MKT Context Commentary — Psalms chapters 34–36
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-34-36.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/psalms.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/psalms.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/psalms.json (philological background)
- data/commentary/jfb/psalms.json (historical context)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ps 34: alphabetic acrostic (22 verses, 22 Hebrew letters); superscription refers to "Abimelech"
  but 1 Sam 21:10–15 names the king Achish — Abimelech is likely a dynastic title for Philistine kings
  (cf. Gen 20:2; 26:1), not a personal name error
- Ps 34:8 "taste and see": probably linked to temple feast of peace offerings (shĕlāmîm);
  sacramental eating as experience of divine favor
- Ps 34:20 "not one bone broken": both a wisdom statement about the righteous and a Passover lamb
  allusion (Exod 12:46; Num 9:12) — cited by John 19:36 for the crucifixion
- Ps 35: three-part lament with individual vow-of-praise refrains; divine warrior imagery dominant
- Ps 36:1b quoted by Paul in Rom 3:18 as the definitive statement of universal human sinfulness
- Ps 36:5–9 uses cosmic dimensions (sky/clouds/mountains/deep) to describe divine character —
  the four paired terms ḥesed, ʾĕmûnāh, ṣĕdāqāh, mišpāṭ form a wisdom theology of God's character
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-context for Psalms 34–36 — an acrostic wisdom psalm (34), an individual lament
#   with divine warrior imagery (35), and a wisdom contrast psalm on the wicked vs. divine character (36).
# CHANGE? If commentary/mkt-context/psalms.json structure changes, update load_comm/save_comm.
# VERIFY: python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-context/psalms.json'));
#   [print(ch, len(d[ch])) for ch in ['34','35','36']]"

PSALMS = {
  "34": {
    "1": '<p>The superscription connects Psalm 34 to David\'s flight to Gath and his feigned madness before the Philistine king (1 Sam 21:10–15). However, that narrative names the king "Achish," while this superscription says "Abimelech" — a discrepancy long noted by commentators. The most plausible explanation is that <em>Abimelech</em> ("my father is king") functioned as a dynastic title for Philistine rulers, much as <em>Pharaoh</em> designated Egyptian kings generically, and <em>Agag</em> was a title for Amalekite kings. This is supported by Gen 20:2 and 26:1, where Abraham and Isaac both encounter someone named Abimelech in similar contexts centuries apart. The psalm itself is a carefully structured alphabetic acrostic: each of the 22 verses begins with a successive letter of the Hebrew alphabet (aleph through taw), a wisdom teaching device signaling comprehensive coverage of the subject.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"My soul boasts in the LORD" — the verb <em>hāllal</em> (to boast, praise, shine) is the root of <em>hallĕlûyāh</em>. The distinction here is between self-boasting (<em>hāllal benapšô</em>), which is condemned in the Psalter (Ps 52:1; 94:4), and boasting in the LORD (<em>hāllal bYHWH</em>, cf. Jer 9:24; 1 Cor 1:31), which is the right orientation of praise. "The humble (<em>ʿănāwîm</em>) will hear and be glad" — the <em>ʿănāwîm</em> are the pious poor, those who have internalized their dependence on God; this is a social and spiritual category that became central to Second Temple piety (the <em>ʿănāwîm</em> of Isaiah 61, the "poor in spirit" of the Beatitudes).</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Magnify the LORD with me and let us exalt his name together" — the invitation to communal praise is characteristic of thanksgiving psalms performed at the temple following personal deliverance. The thanksgiving psalm had a social function: the worshipper who had been delivered would bring an offering and testify publicly in the temple courts, inviting the assembled community to join in praise (cf. Ps 22:22–25; 116:12–14). "His name" — the divine name carried the accumulated weight of all YHWH\'s prior acts of deliverance; to exalt the name is to declare the character it represents.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"I sought the LORD (<em>dāraštî</em>) and he answered me" — <em>dāraš</em> (seek, inquire) is the standard term for consulting the sanctuary oracle or petitioning the temple deity. In ancient Israel, "seeking the LORD" could mean physically going to the sanctuary, consulting a priest, or earnest prayer. The verb here functions as a testimony formula: the speaker reports what happened when they sought YHWH in prayer. "He delivered me from all my fears (<em>mĕgûrôtāy</em>)" — <em>māgôr</em> (fear, dread, terror) from <em>gûr</em> (to sojourn, be a stranger); the fears of one who is without protection in a hostile environment — precisely the David-in-Gath situation of the superscription.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Those who look to him are radiant (<em>nāhărû</em>); their faces will not be ashamed" — <em>nāhar</em> means to shine or to stream (as a river); both meanings carry nuance here. The radiance of those who look to YHWH contrasts with the "shining" of the proud who glorify themselves. Face-shame (<em>bōšet pānîm</em>) in ANE honor-shame culture was the most devastating social consequence — public humiliation before one\'s community. The promise is not merely internal dignity but vindication in the eyes of the community, the restoration of social honor.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"This poor man (<em>ʿānî</em>) cried and the LORD heard" — the verse shifts abruptly to third person, creating a slight puzzle. Many interpreters read it as the psalmist speaking of himself in the third person (distancing himself from his own abasement), which was common in the Psalter and in ANE royal inscriptions. Others read it as a general statement about the pious poor inserted into the personal testimony. The shift from "I" (vv. 3–5) to "this poor man" highlights that the psalmist\'s experience is paradigmatic — it illustrates what the LORD does for all who call on him in their poverty.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"The angel of the LORD (<em>malʾak YHWH</em>) encamps around those who fear him and rescues them" — the <em>malʾak YHWH</em> (messenger/angel of YHWH) is a distinctive presence in the Hebrew Bible who speaks as YHWH himself (Gen 16:7–13; 22:11–18; Exod 3:2; Josh 5:13–15; Judg 2:1–4). This figure simultaneously represents and is identified with YHWH, leading to later theological reflection on divine presence and mediation. The imagery here is military: the angel "encamps" (<em>ḥōneh</em>) like a protective garrison around those who fear God — one warrior deity providing a protective perimeter around the pious.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Taste and see that the LORD is good!" — one of the Psalter\'s most vivid sensory invitations. "Taste" (<em>ṭaʿamû</em>) may carry a specific liturgical reference: in the peace offering (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) worship, the worshipper ate portions of the sacrifice in the temple courts as a feast of communion with God. To eat of the sacrifice was to participate in the divine table — the taste of the offering was meant to convey the goodness of the one worshipped. The invitation to "taste and see" thus may be a literal invitation to join the communal sacrificial feast, in which divine goodness was experienced through the physical act of eating. <em>Ṭôb</em> (good) — divine goodness is both moral excellence and practical beneficence toward those who seek him.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Fear the LORD, you his holy people (<em>qĕdōšāyw</em>)" — <em>qādôš</em> (holy, set apart) applied to the human worshippers of YHWH designates those who belong to the divine sphere through covenant relationship. The <em>qĕdōšîm</em> are the covenant community understood as YHWH\'s holy ones, distinct from the nations. "Those who fear him lack nothing" (<em>ʾên maḥsôr lîrēʾāyw</em>) — the comprehensive sufficiency of divine provision for the covenant community; the same claim as Ps 23 ("I shall not want"). The statement is empirical-covenantal: those within the covenant structure experience its material and spiritual provisions.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Young lions (<em>kĕpîrîm</em>) go hungry and lack food" — the young lion is the apex predator, the creature most capable of obtaining its own food by strength and violence. The shocking reversal: even the mightiest of natural hunters may go without, while "those who seek the LORD lack no good thing." This antithesis situates covenant piety above the food chain itself. In ANE wisdom literature, the power of the strong against the weak was taken as a natural fact; Psalm 34 subverts this by making YHWH\'s provision superior to the strength of the predator.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Come, children, listen to me; I will teach you the fear of the LORD" — this verse signals the explicit wisdom-teaching register of the psalm. The address "children" (<em>bānîm</em>, sons/students) matches the teacher-student address of Proverbs (Prov 1:8; 2:1; 3:1; 4:1; 5:1; 7:1). The psalm shifts from testimony (vv. 1–10) to instruction (vv. 11–22), making explicit the pedagogical function of the thanksgiving form: the public testimony becomes a teaching event. "The fear of the LORD" is the wisdom tradition\'s master concept — not paralytic terror but reverential orientation toward God as the beginning of wisdom (Prov 1:7; 9:10; Ps 111:10).</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Who is the person who desires life (<em>ḥayyîm</em>) and loves long days to enjoy what is good?" — the wisdom question in rhetorical form, expecting the answer "all of us." In the wisdom tradition, long life and enjoyment of good are the fruits of righteous living (Prov 3:1–2, 16; Deut 5:16; 6:2; 11:9). "Life" here is not merely biological existence but flourishing existence — what the OT calls <em>šālôm</em>: wholeness, integration, prosperity within a good life. The question sets up the instruction of vv. 13–14 as the path to this desired outcome.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Keep your tongue from evil and your lips from speaking lies" — speech ethics is a major domain of Second Temple wisdom. Ben Sira (Ecclesiasticus) devotes multiple chapters to the dangers of the tongue (Sir 14:1; 19:4–17; 22:27–23:15; 28:12–26). In the social world of the ancient village, false testimony, slander, and deceptive speech could destroy a person\'s reputation, legal standing, and economic livelihood. The "lying lips" (<em>śĕpātayim mibbĕr mirmāh</em>) echo the legal context of false witness in Exod 20:16 and the covenant curses of Deut 27–28.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Turn from evil and do good; seek peace (<em>šālôm</em>) and pursue it" — the two movement verbs are emphatic: <em>sûr</em> (turn away, remove oneself) and <em>rādap</em> (pursue, chase, hunt). The pursuit of <em>šālôm</em> requires active chase, not passive waiting. <em>Šālôm</em> in its full semantic range is not merely absence of conflict but wholeness, completeness, right relationship between persons and with God. This verse was prominent in Second Temple Judaism as a summary ethical instruction (cf. 1 Pet 3:11, which quotes it, and its echo in the Beatitude "blessed are the peacemakers").</p>',
    "15": '<p>"The LORD\'s eyes are on the righteous and his ears are open to their cry" — the divine senses directed toward the righteous: eyes (watchful care) and ears (responsive attention). This anthropomorphic language maps onto the temple theology in which the divine presence "watches" and "hears" from the sanctuary. Solomon\'s prayer at the temple dedication (1 Kgs 8:29) uses identical language: "May your eyes be open toward this temple night and day, this place of which you said, \'My Name shall be there,\' so that you will hear the prayer your servant prays toward this place."</p>',
    "16": '<p>"The LORD turns his face (<em>pānāyw</em>) against those who do evil, to cut off the memory of them from the earth" — the divine "face" directed against someone is the most severe form of divine opposition (Lev 17:10; 20:3, 5, 6; 26:17; Ezek 14:8; 15:7). This inverts the Aaronic blessing in which the divine face is lifted upon the worshipper (Num 6:25–26). "Cutting off the memory" — the same eradication formula used throughout the Psalter and Deuteronomy for enemies; in ANE culture, to have one\'s name and memory cut off was the ultimate defeat, equivalent to non-existence.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"The righteous cry out (<em>ṣāʿăqû</em>) and the LORD hears; he delivers them from all their troubles" — <em>ṣāʿaq</em> is the urgent cry of distress, the same verb used for the cry of the Israelites in Egypt (Exod 2:23; 3:7, 9) and for the blood of Abel crying from the ground (Gen 4:10). It is more urgent than ordinary prayer — a cry from a situation of genuine danger or oppression. The pattern established here — the righteous cry, YHWH hears, YHWH delivers — is the structural backbone of the entire Psalter\'s theology of prayer.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"The LORD is close to the brokenhearted (<em>nišbĕrê-lēb</em>) and rescues those whose spirit (<em>rûaḥ</em>) is crushed (<em>dakkāʾ</em>)" — <em>šābar lēb</em> (broken heart) is the condition of one whose inner strength has been destroyed by grief, loss, or oppression. <em>Dakkāʾ</em> (crushed) from <em>dākaʾ</em> (to crush, grind down, pulverize) — the most severe form of spiritual depletion. This verse became a foundational text for understanding divine compassion toward the suffering in Second Temple Judaism and in the NT (Isa 57:15; 61:1 — which Jesus applies to himself in Luke 4:18). The irony: precisely when a person is most broken, God is closest — divine proximity is inversely proportional to human strength.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"The righteous face many afflictions (<em>rabbôt rāʿôt</em>)" — the Psalter does not promise immunity from suffering; it promises divine companionship through suffering. This is the antidote to any prosperity-gospel reading of the Psalter. The wisdom tradition is honest about the suffering of the righteous (Job, Ps 73, Lamentations) — the question is not whether suffering occurs but whether YHWH is present within it. "The LORD delivers them from all of them" — the comprehensive deliverance is eschatological as much as historical: the full salvation may await final vindication.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"He protects all his bones; not one of them will be broken" — the language of bone-breaking has a specific legal and cultic background. In the Passover law, the bones of the Passover lamb were not to be broken (Exod 12:46; Num 9:12) — the lamb was to be consumed whole, unbroken. The preservation of the righteous person\'s bones echoes this sacrificial requirement, implicitly comparing the righteous sufferer to the Passover lamb. John 19:36 explicitly cites this verse (or the Passover law it echoes) as fulfilled when the soldiers did not break Jesus\'s legs. The verse thus stands at the intersection of wisdom ethics and sacrificial typology.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Evil will slay the wicked, and those who hate the righteous will be condemned (<em>yĕʾšāmû</em>)" — the retributive theology of the Psalter: evil is self-destructive. <em>Tišlāḥ rāʿāh rāšāʿ</em> (evil slays the wicked) — the instrument of destruction is the wicked\'s own evil, which turns on its owner (the boomerang motif of Pss 7:15–16; 9:15–16; 35:7–8). <em>ʾāšam</em> (to be condemned, bear guilt, be guilty) — in the legal sphere, this is the verdict of criminal guilt; in the cultic sphere, it is the state of incurred guilt requiring atonement. For those who hate the righteous, the guilt they incur is their own sentence.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The LORD redeems (<em>pōdeh</em>) the lives of his servants; none who take refuge (<em>ḥōsîm</em>) in him will be condemned" — <em>pādāh</em> (redeem, ransom) in its original context meant buying back something pledged as collateral or a person sold into slavery; it is an economic-legal metaphor for divine rescue. The <em>ḥôsîm</em> (those who take refuge) is a recurring designation for those who trust in YHWH rather than military strength or wealth (Pss 2:12; 5:11; 17:7; 25:20; 31:19; 37:40). "Will not be condemned (<em>lōʾ yeʾšāmû</em>)" — inverts the condemnation of the wicked in v. 21; the final verse of the acrostic closes the A-to-Z argument: those in YHWH\'s keeping are not under the condemnation that destroys the wicked.</p>',
  },
  "35": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 35 is an individual lament in three clearly marked sections (vv. 1–10, 11–18, 19–28), each ending with a vow to praise God in the assembly. The opening imperative "Contend (<em>rîbāh</em>), O LORD, against those who contend with me" is a lawsuit term: <em>rîb</em> is the legal dispute, the pleading of a case in court. The psalmist summons YHWH as his legal advocate — the one who will argue his case before the divine court. This forensic framing (also Ps 43:1; Isa 49:25; Jer 2:9; 51:36; Mic 7:9) reflects the ancient Israelite institution of the divine judge as the ultimate court of appeal for those who cannot obtain justice in human courts.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Take up your shield (<em>māgēn</em>) and armor (<em>ṣinnāh</em>) and come to my aid" — the divine warrior motif, in which YHWH is imagined as a fully armed soldier fighting for his people. Two types of shield are mentioned: the <em>māgēn</em> (small round shield carried on the arm) and the <em>ṣinnāh</em> (the large full-body shield). The armament request is hyperbolic — the psalmist calls on the entire arsenal of the divine warrior. This divine warrior imagery is central to the Exodus tradition (Exod 14:14; 15:3), the prophets (Isa 42:13; 59:16–17; Zeph 3:17), and appears in the armor of God metaphor of Eph 6:10–17.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Brandish the spear (<em>ḥănît</em>) and block the path" — the specific weapons named here are those of the professional warrior class: the <em>ḥănît</em> (long battle-spear) was the characteristic weapon of the Philistine giant (1 Sam 17:7; 2 Sam 21:19). The divine warrior who carries such weapons surpasses even the feared Philistine heavy infantry. "Say to my soul, \'I am your deliverance (<em>yĕšûʿātĕkā</em>)!\'" — YHWH speaking into the <em>nepeš</em> (soul, inner self) is the personal dimension of divine assurance: not just external military action but an inner word of peace. The term <em>yĕšûʿāh</em> (salvation, deliverance) is the root of the name Yeshua/Jesus.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Let those who seek my life be put to shame (<em>yēbōšû</em>) and humiliated" — the shame petition is a recurring feature of lament psalms (Pss 25:3; 31:17; 40:14; 69:6; 70:2; 71:24). In ANE honor-shame culture, shame before the community was the severest social consequence — a reversal of social standing. The petition is not merely personal vindication but the public restoration of honor that has been taken away by the enemy\'s slanders and attacks. "Those who plot evil against me be turned back in confusion (<em>wĕyissōgû ʾāḥôr wĕyikālamû</em>)" — the double movement of retreat and disgrace.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Let them be like chaff (<em>môṣ</em>) before the wind" — the threshing floor analogy. In ancient Israelite agriculture, grain was threshed by trampling (oxen or teams walking over the stalks) and then winnowed by tossing into the air so the wind could carry away the chaff while the grain fell. The chaff that blew away was worthless, insubstantial, easily dispersed. This imagery appears in Ps 1:4 for the wicked in contrast to the righteous person who is like a firmly planted tree. "The angel of the LORD driving them off" — the same divine warrior-messenger who protected the righteous in Ps 34:7 here pursues the wicked.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Make their path dark and treacherous (<em>ḥălaqlaqqôt</em>), with the angel of the LORD pursuing them" — <em>ḥălaqlaqqôt</em> (slippery, treacherous places) from <em>ḥālaq</em> (smooth, slippery). In hilly terrain, smooth rock faces and loose scree were genuinely dangerous; the metaphor of a slippery path for those being pursued invokes the genuine terror of flight through hostile terrain (cf. Jer 23:12; Pss 73:18). The pursuing angel here mirrors the pursuing angel of Num 22:22–27, who blocked Balaam\'s path. The divine pursuer makes escape impossible.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Without reason (<em>ḥinnām</em>) they concealed their net to trap me; without reason they dug a pit for my life" — <em>ḥinnām</em> (without cause, gratuitously, for nothing) is the same word used in Job 1:9 when the satan asks if Job fears God "for nothing" (<em>ḥinnām</em>), and in Job 2:3 where God says the satan moved against Job "without cause." The word marks the moral bankruptcy of the attack: there is no legitimate grievance, no provocation, no justification. Hunting traps (nets, pits) were the standard OT metaphor for hidden schemes and ambushes (Pss 9:15; 31:4; 57:6; 140:5; 141:9–10; Jer 18:22).</p>',
    "8": '<p>"May ruin overtake him when he least expects it" — the boomerang principle: the trap designed for the righteous catches the trapper instead. This retributive pattern runs through the Psalter and wisdom literature (Prov 26:27; Eccl 10:8; Sir 27:26–27). "The net he hid catch him; may he fall into it to his destruction (<em>bĕšôʾāh</em>)" — <em>šôʾāh</em> is the same root as the Hebrew word for the Holocaust (destruction, catastrophic ruin). The poetic justice is complete: the pit dug for another becomes one\'s own grave.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Then my soul will rejoice in the LORD, exulting in his deliverance" — the vow-of-praise formula that ends the first section. The future joy anticipated in prayer is a distinctive feature of the lament-to-praise movement in the Psalter: the psalmist commits in advance to praise the God who has not yet acted, expressing confidence that deliverance is coming. This "anticipatory praise" (sometimes called the "psalm of trust" element within laments) is the most distinctive theological contribution of the lament genre: praise uttered in the darkness before the dawn.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Every bone in my body will say, \'LORD, who is like you?\'" — the totality of the person (every bone = the whole physical self) engaged in praise. "Who rescues the poor (<em>ʿānî</em>) from those who overpower them" — the divine champion of the weak is one of the central themes of the Psalter and the prophets. The rhetorical question <em>mî kāmôkā</em> (who is like you?) is the incomparability formula, the most emphatic assertion of monotheistic uniqueness. It appears in the Song of the Sea (Exod 15:11), in the prophets (Isa 40:18; 46:5; Mic 7:18), and throughout the Psalter as the climactic proclamation of divine uniqueness.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Malicious witnesses (<em>ʿēdê ḥāmās</em>) rise against me; they charge me with things I know nothing of" — the legal setting is explicit. <em>ʿēd ḥāmās</em> (witness of violence/malice) is the false witness condemned in the Decalogue (Exod 20:16: "do not give false testimony") and in the Deuteronomic law of witnesses (Deut 19:15–21). In the legal system of ancient Israel, testimony by two or three witnesses was required for conviction; false accusers who bore false witness received the penalty that would have been inflicted on the accused (Deut 19:19). The psalmist faces the worst social-legal threat of the ancient world: coordinated perjury before an Israelite court.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"They repay me evil for good, leaving my soul (<em>napšî</em>) desolate (<em>šĕkôl</em>)" — the inversion of reciprocity. In ANE honor culture, reciprocal gift exchange and loyalty were the social glue of community life. To repay evil for good was the most profound violation of social covenant (cf. Prov 17:13; Gen 44:4; 1 Sam 25:21; John 10:32). <em>Šĕkôl</em> (desolate, bereaved, like a parent whose child has died) — the root of <em>šĕkôl</em> (bereavement after the death of children); to be left <em>šĕkôl</em> is to experience the most devastating social loss known in antiquity, the cutting off of one\'s line.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"But when they were sick, I wore sackcloth (<em>śāq</em>) and humbled myself with fasting" — sackcloth was a coarse garment of dark goat-hair worn as the standard dress of mourning, fasting, and penitence throughout the ancient Near East (1 Kgs 21:27; 2 Kgs 6:30; Neh 9:1; Isa 58:5; Jon 3:5–8). Donning sackcloth for someone else\'s illness was the ultimate expression of solidarity — treating their pain as your own grief. Fasting accompanied sackcloth as the bodily practice of prayer, intensifying the petition (Ps 69:10; 109:24; Ezra 8:23; Esth 4:3).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"I acted like one grieving for a dear friend (<em>ʾōhēb</em>) or brother; I bowed down in mourning as one who weeps for his mother" — the depth of social solidarity expressed here is remarkable: the psalmist mourned for his enemies as if they were his closest kin — friend, brother, mother. ANE mourning customs included wearing sackcloth, tearing garments, putting dust or ashes on the head, refusing to eat, and verbal lamentation (Gen 37:34; 2 Sam 1:11–12; 3:31–32; 13:19). To perform all these customs for an enemy who has now turned on you is the deepest form of social betrayal: the person you wept for now brings false charges against you.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"But when I stumbled, they rejoiced and gathered together; attackers assembled against me" — Schadenfreude (joy at another\'s misfortune) was a recognized moral vice in both Israel and the ancient Near East. Ezek 25:3, 6 and Lam 2:15–16 record the enemies of Israel rejoicing over Jerusalem\'s fall with the same <em>šāmaḥ</em> (rejoice) verb. The gathering of accusers and attackers when the psalmist stumbled suggests a social situation in which a change of fortune (illness, legal setback, military defeat) was treated as evidence of guilt — the friends who were mourned now become accusers.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Like godless mockers at a banquet (<em>ḥanpê-laʿăgê māʿôg</em>), they gnashed their teeth at me" — a notoriously difficult Hebrew phrase. <em>Ḥanpê</em> (godless, profane) + <em>laʿăgê</em> (mockers) + <em>māʿôg</em> (cake, pastry; or a place name). The most defensible reading: "like the profane mockers at a feast [who mock the absent]" — the banquet setting where mockery and slander of the absent (table gossip, symposium wit at others\' expense) was a recognized social practice. "Gnashing teeth" (<em>ḥāraq šinnayim</em>) is the physical expression of aggressive rage or contempt (Pss 37:12; 112:10; Lam 2:16; Acts 7:54).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"How long, O Lord (<em>ʾădōnāy</em>), will you keep watching (<em>tirʾeh</em>)?" — the "how long?" question is the characteristic temporal challenge of the lament psalm (Pss 6:3; 13:1–2; 74:10; 80:4; 90:13; 94:3; Hab 1:2; 2:6). Divine watching without acting is experienced as cruel indifference — the judge who sees the crime and does nothing. "Rescue my precious self (<em>napšî</em>) from these lions" — the lion metaphor returns (cf. v. 10 above; Ps 22:12–13, 21). The <em>yĕḥîdāh</em> (my precious one, my only one) is a particularly intimate self-designation — one\'s unique, irreplaceable life.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"I will give you thanks in the great assembly (<em>qāhāl rāb</em>); among the vast multitude (<em>ʿam ʿāṣûm</em>) I will praise you" — the second vow of praise closes the second section. The public assembly is a key setting for thanksgiving in the Psalter. The peace offering feast (cf. Ps 34:8 above) was performed in the temple courts and included a public proclamation of the deliverance received (cf. Ps 22:22–25; 40:9–10; 66:16–19; 116:14–19). To vow public praise is to commit to the social performance of gratitude — the testimony that invites the community into the psalmist\'s experience of divine faithfulness.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"Do not let my enemies gloat over me without cause (<em>ḥinnām</em>); do not let those who hate me without reason (<em>šĕqer</em>) exchange knowing glances" — <em>ḥinnām</em> appears again (cf. v. 7): the gratuitous, unprovoked nature of the hostility is emphasized. "Exchange knowing glances (<em>yiqrĕṣû-ʿāyin</em>)" — the wink or meaningful glance exchanged between conspirators was the non-verbal communication of shared deception in ancient social settings (Prov 6:13; 10:10). It was the signal of those who coordinate slander without using words that could be overheard.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"They do not pursue peace (<em>šālôm</em>); instead they invent slanders (<em>mirmôt dĕbārê</em>) against those who live quietly in the land" — the "quiet in the land" (<em>rĕgîʿê ʾāreṣ</em>) is an unusual phrase sometimes taken as a technical term for the peaceful peasant class, those living without political prominence and without causing harm. The attack on those who "live quietly" — who seek no conflict — makes the hostility even more gratuitous. This is not a conflict between powers; it is the persecution of the unassuming by the politically connected. Second Temple Jewish interpretation often read the "quiet in the land" as the pious remnant (<em>ʿănāwîm</em>) persecuted by the powerful.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"They open their mouths wide against me and say, \'Aha! Aha! (<em>heʾāḥ heʾāḥ</em>) We have seen it with our own eyes!\'" — the exclamation <em>heʾāḥ</em> is a gloating cry of triumph at another\'s downfall, used for mock-triumph over an enemy (Pss 40:15; 70:3; Ezek 25:3; 26:2; 36:2). The claim "we have seen it with our own eyes" is a legal formula — eyewitness testimony was the strongest form of evidence in ancient courts. The adversaries are manufacturing false eyewitness accounts, the severest form of legal perjury.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"You have seen this (<em>rāʾîtāh</em>), LORD; do not stay silent (<em>al-teḥĕraš</em>)" — the psalmist turns the courtroom language against the accusers: YHWH has seen what they claim to have witnessed; divine testimony trumps human perjury. "Do not stay silent" — divine silence in the face of injustice is experienced as complicity (cf. Hab 1:2, 13; Ps 83:1). The petition for YHWH to speak is simultaneously a petition for action: when God speaks, things happen.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Arise (<em>hāʿîrāh</em>) and wake yourself (<em>hāqîṣāh</em>) to my defense" — the "rise up" imperative battle-cry (cf. Num 10:35; Pss 3:7; 7:6; 9:19; 10:12) is here doubled with "wake yourself," creating an image of the sleeping deity who must be roused. This anthropomorphism reaches its most dramatic expression in Ps 44:23 ("Awake, O Lord! Why do you sleep?") and its gentle negation in Ps 121:4 ("He who guards Israel will neither slumber nor sleep"). The tension between the sleeping/silent God and the responsive God is honestly maintained in the Psalter without easy resolution.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Vindicate me, LORD my God, according to your righteousness (<em>ṣidqĕkā</em>)" — the appeal to divine righteousness as the basis of vindication invokes the covenant character of YHWH. <em>Ṣādaqāh</em> (righteousness) in the legal sphere means the right order of things — what is due to each party in a dispute. God\'s righteousness is not a demanding standard the psalmist must meet but the character that drives God to restore right order when it has been violated. The same appeal appears in Ps 31:1; 71:2; 143:1, 11.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Do not let them say in their hearts, \'Aha, just what we wanted!\'" — the language of desire satisfied (<em>heʾāḥ napšênû</em>, literally "our soul says aha!") echoes the gloating of v. 21. The petition reaches into the adversaries\' inner life — not merely their outward triumph but the inner satisfaction of appetite achieved. "We have devoured him (<em>bĕlaʿănûhû</em>)" — the swallowing image (cf. Lam 2:16; Ps 124:3) presents the enemy as predator consuming prey, the apex-predator imagery of the psalms of persecution.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Let all who rejoice at my misfortune be put to shame and humiliated together" — the shame-reversal petition: those who enjoyed the psalmist\'s shame will experience shame themselves. "Clothed with shame and disgrace (<em>ʿōṭû-bōšet ûkĕlimmāh</em>)" — shame is a garment that visibly marks the one who wears it in ancient honor-shame culture. The image of being "clothed" in shame or glory occurs throughout the Psalter and the prophets (Ps 93:1 — YHWH clothed in majesty; Ps 109:18 — the wicked clothed in curses; Isa 61:3 — the garment of praise for the spirit of heaviness).</p>',
    "27": '<p>"Let those who delight in my vindication (<em>ṣidqî</em>) shout for joy and say, \'Great is the LORD, who takes pleasure in the welfare (<em>šālôm</em>) of his servant!\'" — the communal dimension of individual vindication: the psalmist\'s restoration is not only a personal event but a liturgical occasion for all who have invested hope in YHWH\'s justice. "Those who delight in my vindication" are the solidarity community — the pious who have prayed for the falsely accused. YHWH\'s "pleasure in the welfare of his servant" (<em>ḥāpēṣ šĕlôm ʿabdô</em>) grounds the petition in divine character: the God who takes pleasure in human flourishing is the basis for expecting deliverance.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Then my tongue will proclaim your righteousness and your praise all day long" — the third and final vow of praise closes the psalm. The temporal marker "all day long" (<em>kol-hayyôm</em>) indicates the continuous, unending character of the praise: not a single act of thanksgiving but a lifetime orientation. The psalm began with a forensic challenge (contend for me, v. 1) and ends with a public declaration (my tongue will proclaim) — the movement from crisis to testimony, from silence to speech, from fear to praise, is the structural arc of the entire Psalter\'s lament genre.</p>',
  },
  "36": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 36 is unusual in its structure: a wisdom meditation on wickedness (vv. 1–4) followed immediately by a hymn to divine character (vv. 5–9) and a brief petition with confidence statement (vv. 10–12). The superscription calls it a psalm of "David the servant of the LORD" — the <em>ʿebed YHWH</em> (servant of the LORD) designation links the author to the great servant figures of the prophets. The opening is remarkable: "the voice of transgression (<em>nĕʾum-pešaʿ</em>) speaks deep within the heart of the wicked." <em>Nĕʾum</em> is the prophetic oracle formula ("oracle of the LORD," <em>nĕʾum YHWH</em>); here wickedness itself speaks with prophetic authority from within the wicked person\'s <em>lēb</em> (heart). Sin is personified as an inner oracle, a demonic voice dictating the wicked\'s inner life.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"For he deceives himself into thinking his guilt cannot be discovered and condemned (<em>limsōʾ ʿăwōnô lĕśānōʾ</em>)" — the self-deception of the wicked is the theme. <em>Hĕlîq</em> (<em>hāllaq</em>, to be smooth, flattering) — the wicked person speaks smoothly to himself, self-flattering inner speech that makes his own guilt invisible. The result: there is no "fear of God before his eyes" — quoted by Paul in Rom 3:18 as the defining statement of universal human sinfulness and the culmination of his catena of OT texts demonstrating universal guilt (Rom 3:10–18). In Paul\'s reading, this is not only the condition of the wicked but the condition of all humans apart from divine grace.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"His mouth pours out wickedness (<em>ʾāwen</em>) and deception (<em>mirmāh</em>)" — <em>ʾāwen</em> (wickedness, vanity, emptiness, idolatry) is one of the Psalter\'s key moral terms, combining the meanings of wickedness, emptiness, and often idolatrous practice. The coupling of <em>ʾāwen</em> with <em>mirmāh</em> (treachery, deception) describes speech that is both morally corrupt and strategically deceptive. "He has stopped acting wisely (<em>ḥādal lĕhaśkîl</em>)" — <em>śākal</em> (to act wisely, have insight, prosper) is the wisdom vocabulary; to cease from wisdom is to abandon the fundamental orientation of covenant life. This cessation is presented as a deliberate act, not merely ignorance.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"On his bed he hatches schemes (<em>yĕḥaššōb ʾāwen</em>)" — the privacy of the bed where no social constraint operates becomes the laboratory of wickedness. The bed as the place of wicked scheming also appears in Mic 2:1: "Woe to those who plan iniquity and devise evil on their beds." "He places himself on a path that is not good (<em>ʿal-derek lōʾ-ṭôb yityaṣṣēb</em>)" — the deliberate positioning on an evil path; <em>yāṣab</em> (to stand firm, position oneself) suggests intentional commitment, not accidental wandering. "He refuses to reject evil (<em>rāʿ lōʾ yimʾās</em>)" — the active refusal to turn from evil. The portrait of wickedness in vv. 1–4 is complete: inner oracle, self-deception, wicked speech, cessation of wisdom, nocturnal scheming, deliberate path-setting, refusal of repentance.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Your steadfast love (<em>ḥasdĕkā</em>), LORD, reaches to the heavens (<em>bašāmayim</em>); your faithfulness (<em>ʾĕmûnātĕkā</em>) extends to the clouds" — after the claustrophobic portrait of wickedness (vv. 1–4), the psalm explodes into cosmic scope. The divine attributes are mapped onto the vertical dimensions of the cosmos: <em>ḥesed</em> (steadfast love, covenant loyalty) reaches to the heavens; <em>ʾĕmûnāh</em> (faithfulness, reliability, steadiness) extends to the clouds. The heavens and clouds together represent the upper atmospheric sphere — but also beyond it: the attributes of God transcend even the highest created reality.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Your righteousness (<em>ṣidqātĕkā</em>) towers like the mighty mountains (<em>harĕrê-ʾēl</em>); your judgments (<em>mišpāṭêkā</em>) plunge as deep as the ocean (<em>tĕhôm rabbāh</em>)" — the four paired terms (<em>ḥesed</em>, <em>ʾĕmûnāh</em>, <em>ṣĕdāqāh</em>, <em>mišpāṭ</em>) constitute the core vocabulary of divine character in the wisdom and prophetic traditions. <em>Harĕrê-ʾēl</em> ("mountains of God/El") — the superlative use of the divine name ʾEl means "towering/mighty mountains," not mountains literally belonging to God. <em>Tĕhôm rabbāh</em> (the great deep) — the primordial ocean-abyss of Gen 1:2, Job 38:16, the symbol of immeasurable depth. "You preserve both human and animal (<em>ʾādām ûbĕhēmāh</em>)" — the scope of divine care encompasses all living creatures, both human and non-human (echoing Ps 104 and anticipating the Noahic covenant).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"How priceless (<em>mah-yāqār</em>) is your steadfast love, O God! The children of humanity (<em>bĕnê ʾādām</em>) take refuge under the shadow of your wings (<em>bĕṣēl kĕnāpêkā</em>)" — the wing-shadow image occurs throughout the Psalter (Pss 17:8; 57:1; 61:4; 63:7; 91:4) and in the Torah (Deut 32:11 — God as eagle bearing Israel on his wings). The image draws on multiple registers: (a) the cherubim wings spread over the ark in the Holy of Holies, representing divine protection; (b) the maternal bird covering her chicks; (c) the Boaz-Ruth idiom of covenant protection (Ruth 2:12: "under whose wings you have come to take refuge"). The temple context may be primary: the ark-cherubim wings were the visible symbol of divine shelter in the sanctuary.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"They feast on the richness of your house (<em>yirwĕyûn middeśen bêtêkā</em>)" — the language of the temple feast is explicit: <em>dešen</em> (fatness, richness) is the abundance of the peace offering meal. In the temple liturgy, the peace offering (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) was the only sacrifice where the worshipper ate — portions of the cooked meat were eaten by the priest, the Levites, and the worshipper\'s household in the temple courts. To eat from the "fatness of your house" is to participate in this communal sacred meal. "The river of your pleasures (<em>naḥal ʿădānêkā</em>)" — <em>ʿeden</em> (pleasure, delight, Eden); the "river of delights" evokes the rivers of Paradise (Gen 2:10–14; cf. Ezek 47:1–12; Rev 22:1–2). The temple is the locus of Edenic life restored.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"For with you is the fountain of life (<em>mĕqôr ḥayyîm</em>); by your light we see light (<em>bĕʾôrĕkā nirʾeh-ʾôr</em>)" — two of the most theologically dense phrases in the Psalter. <em>Mĕqôr ḥayyîm</em> (fountain/spring of life) — the life that springs from God himself; not merely physical life but the fullness of existence, all goodness and blessing. In Jeremiah\'s polemic against idolatry, YHWH is "the fountain of living waters" that Israel has abandoned in favor of broken cisterns (Jer 2:13; 17:13). "By your light we see light" — the divine light that makes all seeing possible; not just one light source among others but the light that enables all perception. John 1:4–9 develops this into the theology of the Logos as the light that enlightens every person.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Extend (<em>mĕšōk</em>) your steadfast love to those who know you (<em>lĕyōdĕʿêkā</em>)" — the petition that follows the meditation: the cosmic character of divine love (vv. 5–9) must reach the specific covenant community. <em>Māšak</em> (draw out, extend, prolong) — the same verb used in the Song of Songs for the king drawing the beloved toward him (Song 1:4). "Those who know you" is the covenant insider designation — not intellectual knowledge but relational, covenantal knowing (Gen 4:1; Hos 2:20; 4:1–6; John 17:3). "Your righteousness to the upright in heart (<em>lĕyišrê-lēb</em>)" — the upright of heart are those whose inner orientation aligns with the covenant order.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Let not the foot of arrogance (<em>regle gaʾăwāh</em>) trample me (<em>tĕbōʾēnî</em>), nor the hand of the wicked drive me from my place" — the petition uses two concrete physical images: the trampling foot and the driving hand. In ANE warfare, the king stood with his foot on the neck of the defeated enemy (Josh 10:24; Ps 110:1) as the physical symbol of total subjugation. The arrogant foot that tramples is the foot of the conqueror. "My place" (<em>tĕnîdēnî</em>) — being "driven from one\'s place" is being expelled from land, community, and covenant status.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"There the evildoers lie fallen; they have been thrust down and cannot get up" — the prophetic-perfect tense: the fall of the wicked is narrated as already accomplished, the certainty of divine justice so complete that it is spoken in the past tense. "Cannot rise" (<em>yākĕlû qûm</em>) — the permanent, irreversible nature of the fall. The final verse closes the psalm on the note of eschatological confidence: the vast wickedness portrayed in vv. 1–4 and the cosmic goodness portrayed in vv. 5–9 resolve in the assurance that the wicked will fall and the righteous who take refuge in YHWH\'s love (v. 7) will be sustained. The structure of the psalm — wickedness / divine character / petition / prophetic confidence — is itself a theological argument for trusting the God whose love exceeds the heavens.</p>',
  },
}

